    'vertigo-balance-disorders' => [
        'details' => "Vertigo — the false sensation that you or the world around you is spinning — is one of the most distressing symptoms a person can experience, and one of the most misunderstood. It is not a disease itself but a symptom, most often arising from the balance organs of the inner ear.\n\nAccurate diagnosis is everything in vertigo care. Our dedicated vertigo clinic uses advanced vestibular testing — including videonystagmography (VNG), positional testing and balance assessment — to pinpoint the exact cause, whether it's BPPV (loose crystals in the inner ear), vestibular neuritis, Ménière's disease or another disorder.\n\nMost vertigo is very treatable once correctly diagnosed. Simple repositioning manoeuvres resolve BPPV in a session or two; other conditions respond to medication, dietary changes and structured vestibular rehabilitation therapy, where our therapists retrain your balance system with targeted exercises.",
        'faqs' => [
            ['question' => 'Is vertigo the same as dizziness?', 'answer' => "Not exactly. Dizziness is a broad term covering light-headedness, unsteadiness and faintness. Vertigo specifically means a spinning sensation — you feel like you or your surroundings are moving when they are not. The distinction matters because it points to different causes."],
            ['question' => 'What is BPPV and can it be cured?', 'answer' => 'BPPV (Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo) is the most common cause of vertigo — tiny calcium crystals in the inner ear shift out of place and trigger brief spinning spells with head movement. It is highly treatable: a simple in-clinic repositioning manoeuvre resolves most cases within one or two sessions.'],
            ['question' => 'When is vertigo a sign of something serious?', 'answer' => 'Seek immediate care if vertigo comes with severe headache, double vision, slurred speech, weakness, or difficulty walking — these need urgent evaluation. Most vertigo, however, originates in the inner ear and is not dangerous, though it should still be properly diagnosed.'],
            ['question' => 'What happens during vestibular testing?', 'answer' => 'You will wear special goggles that record your eye movements while we guide you through head and body positions, and gentle stimulation of the balance system. The tests are painless and typically take 45-60 minutes, giving us a detailed picture of how your balance organs are functioning.'],
