            ['question' => 'My child has frequent ear infections. When is surgery considered?', 'answer' => 'Occasional ear infections are normal in childhood. We consider grommets (ventilation tubes) when infections are frequent — typically more than 3-4 in six months — or when persistent fluid behind the eardrum ("glue ear") affects hearing for over three months, especially if speech is being affected.'],
            ['question' => 'Do tonsils and adenoids really need to be removed?', 'answer' => 'Only for the right reasons. We recommend removal when enlarged tonsils or adenoids cause obstructed breathing during sleep, repeated severe infections, or persistent ear problems — not for occasional sore throats. Many children outgrow the problem as their airway develops.'],
