    'sleep-apnea-treatment' => [
        'details' => "Snoring is often dismissed as a nuisance, but loud, regular snoring with pauses in breathing may signal obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) — a condition where the airway repeatedly collapses during sleep, starving the body of oxygen dozens of times every hour. Untreated, it raises the risk of high blood pressure, heart disease, diabetes and daytime accidents.\n\nOur sleep clinic begins with a thorough airway evaluation and a sleep study to measure exactly what happens while you sleep — how often breathing pauses, how deeply oxygen drops, and where in the airway the obstruction occurs.\n\nTreatment is matched to the cause and severity. Many patients do well with CPAP therapy, weight management and positional therapy. Where a specific anatomical blockage exists — a deviated septum, enlarged tonsils, or excess palate tissue — surgical correction can reduce or even eliminate the problem. In children, removing enlarged tonsils and adenoids is often curative.",
        'faqs' => [
            ['question' => 'How do I know if my snoring is sleep apnea?', 'answer' => 'Warning signs include pauses in breathing witnessed by a partner, waking with a gasp or choking, morning headaches, dry mouth, and feeling unrefreshed or sleepy during the day despite a full night in bed. A sleep study gives a definitive answer.'],
            ['question' => 'What happens in a sleep study?', 'answer' => 'A sleep study records your breathing, oxygen levels, heart rate and sleep quality overnight. Depending on your case, it can often be done in the comfort of your own home with a portable device we provide, or in a monitored lab setting.'],
            ['question' => 'Is CPAP the only treatment for sleep apnea?', 'answer' => 'No. CPAP is highly effective and often the first-line treatment for moderate to severe OSA, but alternatives include oral appliances, weight reduction, positional therapy, and surgery to correct specific anatomical blockages. The right choice depends on your severity and airway anatomy.'],
            ['question' => 'Can children have sleep apnea?', 'answer' => 'Yes — and it is frequently missed. In children, enlarged tonsils and adenoids are the usual cause, and symptoms include snoring, restless sleep, mouth-breathing, bedwetting and daytime behavioural issues. Unlike adults, surgery is often curative in children.'],
